The `zerorpc` helper is very helpful (eh!), and actually, I start 99% of the ZeroRPC servers that I write with `zerorpc --server`, rather than writing a custom script.

However, I also want to do the following:
- enable a specific middleware;
- configure `logging`.

I currently work around the problem by enabling middlewares and setting up logging within the module loaded by `zerorpc --server`; but this leads to code repetition, and is therefore a Bad Thing.

I would love to have (at least) one of the following options:
- the `zerorpc` helper would automatically try to import a module named `zerorpc_settings` (and fail silently if this raises an `ImportError`);
- the `zerorpc` helper would automatically try to import the module indicated by the environment variable `ZERORPC_SETTINGS_MODULE` (if it is set);
- the `zerorpc` helper would allow an optional command-line flag, `--settings`, indicating the name of the module to import;
- if just importing a module feels weak, we could specify a callable instead (and the environment variable would become `ZERORPC_SETTINGS_CALLABLE`).

I'm willing to implement any of those, as long as I know that it has a chance to be merged (provided that the implementation isn't ugly nor kill baby seals).

What do you think, @bombela ?

I have one terminal window that is busy creating a conda environment (`conda create -n foo ...`.  This takes 10-15 minutes.  In another terminal window I want to build a conda package (`conda build conda.recipe`).  Perhaps in another terminal window I want to build a different conda package.  Right now I can't do the first two due to the way conda does locking.  I'd like to be able to at least do the first two concurrently, and ideally be able to concurrently build multiple conda packages (which I believe is also not possible right now).

